<subSubSection id="A029B254E84D0A018A0B09B314D62F9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="E7620281F7EFEA7D5E7A513DE295F128" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B68A8F59AED5690D437094DAEC14B18F" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Flowering June to July, fruiting July to August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63F7B5F884A25C2A2194BBD3B51B929C" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E182C39DFAF96041DD6B058C299ECF69" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8273F07B3B9D5C3E316E20DB8C2E573F" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">
The specific epithet is based on the name of the town, En-cheng, where 
<taxonomicName id="88E163772759096367C3B84ADA5D3DC6" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="B." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="B. enchengensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="enchengensis">
<emphasis id="5025DD6AB1B7C7ED6281D2B531C0AE9B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">B. enchengensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is discovered.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
